==Old English==
===Etymology===
Cognate with Old Saxon ''druht-'' (in compounds), Old Frisian [[dracht]], [[drecht]] (Frisian [[dregte]]), Old High German [[truht]], [[trut]], Old Norse [[drótt]].  Related to [[dreogan|drēogan]].

===Pronunciation===
{{IPA|/dryçt/}}

===Noun===
'''dryht''' ''f'' (plural '''[[dryhte]]''' or '''[[dryhta]]'''; ''accusative singular'' '''[[dryhte]]''' or '''dryht''')
# ''(poetic)'' [[troop]], [[army]]
# ''(in plural, poetic)'' [[men]], [[mankind]]

